Review: Wonderful images in service of a lesser story than the first installment. A fun time with our friends the cenobites is always a welcome joy, and I am glad to resume the action from the first film. Less coherent ideas and a big bad who is more interesting to look at than to watch don’t help a meandering narrative. I wouldn’t hold these complaints against Hellbound if I didn’t hold the original in such high esteem.

Review: Hopefully more people will watch this solid short with a delightfully crackly transfer and wonderful 80s colors. With stories that are underrepresented in the film canon and the popular culture landscape, it’s always refreshing to be reminded that people have been asserting their place for longer than we know. I’m glad to have seen this, and I frankly wish I could see more of the lives of these characters. Such is the struggle with a short.

Review: My partner and I have been talking frequently about a Midwestern Gothic, and I think the driving scenes in this encapsulate that aesthetic. Emptiness, loneliness, and dread are over each hill, next to the electrical poles, or over a dirt road. Not as much feel bad media as I’d anticipated, solid double with Nightcrawler.
